<article id="node-16962">
<h1 >3.4.8.70 Value of Farm for RAFS</h1>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> THIS SCHEME CLOSED on 31 July 2001 and the following INFORMATION is FOR HISTORICAL PURPOSES ONLY.</p>
<h2>Summary</h2>
<p>Participation in <a href="../../../acronyms#rafs" title="Retirement assistance for farmers scheme">RAFS</a> is limited to farmers, their partners or former partners who have ownership of a farm/s (<a href="../../../1/1/f/100">1.1.F.100</a>) and farm assets worth up to $500,000. This topic explains the issues surrounding the valuation of the farm/s and farm assets.</p>
<h2>What is the net farm value?</h2>
<p>The net value of the farm enterprise (<a href="../../../1/1/f/110">1.1.F.110</a>) is the aggregate of all primary production (<a href="../../../1/1/p/389">1.1.P.389</a>) assets and liabilities.</p>
<p><strong>Exceptions:</strong> The market value of the house and curtilage does NOT count toward the total value, IF the farmer retains a life, freehold or leasehold interest in it.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> An applicant who has a pastoral lease on a farm will not be able to hold a life interest in the farmhouse and curtilage. However, they will be able to hold a leasehold interest in the farmhouse and curtilage from the eligible descendant.</p>
</div>
<p>If the descendant already has a qualifying interest (<a href="../../../1/1/q/30">1.1.Q.30</a>) in the farm, then the value of that interest is also disregarded from the total farm value.</p>
<p>These points are explained in the rest of this topic.</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Act reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.au/Series/C2004A04121" title="Social Security Act 1991">SSAct</a> section 1121A Effect of certain liabilities on value of assets used in primary production</p>
</div>
<h2>The $500,000 limit</h2>
<p>The $500,000 limit applies to the combined value of ALL farms in which the farmer has a qualifying interest, NOT each farm. This includes the total value of farm enterprises where the farmer is in partnership (<a href="../../../1/1/p/95">1.1.P.95</a>).</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> A farmer owns a $300,000 property outright, and is also a 50% partner in another property valued at $280,000. This farmer therefore has a qualifying interest in farm assets that exceed the $500,000 limit.</p>
</div>
<p>Different provisions apply however if the eligible descendant/s already has a qualifying interest in the farm or farm assets. These provisions are explained in the referenced topic.</p>
<p>The limit applies to the following, regardless of how many farms are involved:</p>
<ul><li>the qualifying farmer (<a href="../../../1/1/q/20">1.1.Q.20</a>), OR</li>
<li>the qualifying farmer and their partner, OR</li>
<li>the former partner of a qualifying farmer, OR</li>
<li>a group of retiring farmers who are partners in a farm (see example).</li>
</ul><div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> A farm enterprise valued at $700,000 is owned by 2 brothers, each owning a half share valued at $350,000. In this case, the retiring farmer cannot qualify for RAFS.</p>
</div>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="90">3.4.8.90</a> RAFS - Descendant Already has Part Ownership</p>
</div>
<h2>Valuations</h2>
<p>The farmland will need to be valued by the Australian Valuation Office unless:</p>
<ul><li>there is a recent valuation on file, OR</li>
<li>the applicant has provided a valuation by a registered professional valuer.</li>
<li>The farming assets e.g. plant, machinery, livestock, milk quotas etc should be valued at book value as shown on the most recent balance sheet for the farm business. There is no requirement to obtain an Australian Valuation Office valuation of these assets.</li>
</ul><div class="reference">
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="../../../4/6/6">4.6.6</a> Determining the Value of an Asset</p>
</div>
